  discoverContents:
  - Name: How to build a Player
    UniqueKey: How to build a Player
    Description: 'If you want to build a player of the demo, you can access the Build
      frontend window using ''File/Build Frontend'' menu item.


      Upon opening
      the window, select the build profile you want, then click the ''Build Selected''
      or ''+Run'' button to build and optionally run the build once it''s ready.'
    Sections: []
  - Name: Spaceship Demo
    UniqueKey: Spaceship Demo
    Description: 'This set of Scenes contains the whole gameplay walkthrough for
      the Spaceship Demo. This window will guide you through all the stages of the
      demo, and will let you access elements that compose the demo.


      <i>If
      this information is displayed in the inspector, you can navigate more easily
      using the ''Help/Discover Spaceship Demo''</i>'
    Sections:
    - Name: Navigating the Walkthrough
      Description: 'Click the list items in the left part of the window in order
        to access various sections of the discovery of this scene.


        The
        navigation is split between different sections:


        <b>Demo Scripted
        Events</b> is the category that define the walktrhough from the start to
        the end of the demo.


        <b>Visual Effects</b> is the section where
        all other things related to VFX will be present. There are some generic effects
        and systems that you will find around, here is a list of points of interest.'
  - Name: Floating Dust
    UniqueKey: Floating Dust
    Description: In order to thicken the atmosphere, lit floating dust is spawned
      around the player and change as the player evolves through the level.
    Sections:
    - Name: Floating Dust
      Description: This effect spawns particles arount the player's camera. It is
        automatically bound to the Main Camera in the graph so there's no configuration
        required.
    - Name: VFXVolumeMixer Setup
      Description: 'Volumes are set so the floating dust changes its ambient color,
        density and opacity throughout the level. '
  - Name: Other Ambient Effects
    UniqueKey: Other Ambient Effects
    Description: Ambient Effects are used to add dynamics to the scene, making it
      credible and lively. The spaceship is populated with many of these around.
    Sections:
    - Name: Root objects for every Room
      Description: Every set of effects is sorted using a root game object
  - Name: Steam Leaks
    UniqueKey: Steam Leaks
    Description: 'Steam leaks are a pretty straightfowrard effects that blow some
      air particles out of worn and damaged air ducts.


      These effects are
      using a simplified lighting model using light probes'
    Sections:
    - Name: Steam Leak (Directional)
      Description: A simple effect with two emitters.
  - Name: Sparkles (Shake)
    UniqueKey: Sparkles (Shake)
    Description: 'The gameplay periodically sends shakes to the scene using broadcast
      messages.

      Every shake can be caught by objects in order to be processed.


      In
      order to spawn sparkles efficiently, we implemented a system with a multiple
      source effect in a single simulation for sparkles.'
    Sections:
    - Name: The Shake Sparkle Effect (for the First Corridor)
      Description: 'This effect is a special blend of the Sparkle effect with very
        few features (no collision, fewer particles, no noise).


        Instead,
        every instance is fed with a list of transforms that are set using a parameter
        binder.

'
  - Name: Big Sparkle Bursts
    UniqueKey: Big Sparkle Bursts
    Description: In the corridors are placed some big sparkle burst effects. These
      are not responding to the shake events but instead spawn particles on their
      own.
    Sections:
    - Name: Sparkle Effects
      Description: 'A simple sparkle effect with synchornized emission. The emission
        is controlled externally by a game object that sends:

        - A VFX Event

        -
        An Audio source random play

        - A toggle for a spotlight (spotlight
        turns itself off after flashing)'
  - Name: 'Intro : Elevator'
    UniqueKey: 'Intro : Elevator'
    Description: 'The elevator introduction introduces the player to the spaceship
      environment.

      While it''s not a playable section, it''s initializing
      the HUD of the player and performs some animation in a timeline.'
    Sections:
    - Name: Intro Timeline
      Description: The intro timeline gathers all animation, audio and script for
        the introduction of the sequence.
    - Name: Animated Door (Intro Specific)
      Description: "The door animation is called by script from a generic template.
        \nIt spawns particles upon opening, using a Visual Effect attached to each
        door.\nIn order to control the spawn and the velocity of the particles, the
        VFX uses a Spawn Over Distance block that computes the velocity of the doors
        based on the timeline animation."
    - Name: HUD Activation
      Description: 'The HUD of the player is also made of particles.


        During
        the introduction, the timeline broadcasts a message that is caught by the
        VirtualCameraManager.


        Upon recieving the message, the <b>InitSequence</b>
        event is sent to the Visual Effect in order to spawn the text and the highlights
        of the meshes in the scene.'
  - Name: 'HoloTable : Alert'
    UniqueKey: 'HoloTable : Alert'
    Description: 'Alert Mode is the final stage of the walkthrough. During this 30
      second state, missiles will hit the ship, and the holographic table will display
      an overview of the battle between the player''s ship and its attackers.


      The
      sequence ends with a big hit, fading to black.'
    Sections:
    - Name: Alert Sequence
      Description: 'The Alert Sequence cuts abruptly the landing site search sequence
        to display a map of the battle between our ship, and its attackers.


        The
        Environment is split through 2 Visual effects, that are gathered into one
        Main VFX one for the grid, one for the clouds and asteroids. This is intended
        for readability.


        Ships are different configuration of the ARUI-Battleship
        VFX with different targets.'
    - Name: Destructibles
      Description: 'During the attack sequence, some props are activated to simulate
        wreck in the bridge room. The sequencing happens using a state machine that
        will act as an activator of other state machines. Every time a HIT_STRONG
        message is sent by the main timeline (missile hit), the Destructible State
        machine advances one state, enabling more havoc.

        Three main Destructibles
        are placed into the scene:

        - Falling Cables (Torn upon activation,
        react to shake and spawn periodically particles)

        - Falling Plates
        (Only Rigid Bodies)

        - Steam Leak Bursts (Composed of one Single
        Spark + Scaled Steam Leak)'
    - Name: 'In Parallel : Core Room'
      Description: During this attack sequence, the core, at the end of the corridor
        depletes, then collapses. The following section depicts the mechanisms used
        to be in sync with this sequence.
  - Name: Security Terminal
    UniqueKey: Security Terminal
    Description: 'After the First Corridor, you encounter your first interaction
      at the security terminal.


      There is an interactive item at the center
      of the room. When approaching this interactive item, the HUD crosshair becomes
      visible, and the light dot can be selected.'
    Sections:
    - Name: Interactive Item
      Description: The Small dot in midair is an interactive element that is reactive
        to the Player Controller. When hovering with the crosshair, it triggers an
        animation and a state change. The visuals are made of a Visual Effect with
        a boolean property (ARUI-Hover)
    - Name: Security Terminal Sequence
      Description: 'The Security Terminal Sequence starts upon activation of the
        Interactive Item.


        It is a timeline sequence that activates many
        Effects.

'
    - Name: Door Openning (After Sequence)
      Description: 'When the sequence is finished, the Door on the right opens to
        provide access to the Bridge Room.


        The door animation is close
        to the introduction sequence animation, and reveals a steam effect upon opening.
        A  Door Steam VFX is triggered and spawns particles accordingly to each door
        movement.'
    - Name: InteractionVolume
      Description: 'The Interaction Volume defines which area will enable the visibility
        of the HUD Crosshair of the player. It uses the VFX Volume Mixer <i>InteractionArea</i>
        parameter to set the value in the HUD VFX.


        (The HUD VFX is instanced
        in the VirtualCameraManager prefab)'
  - Name: 'Bridge Room : HoloTable'
    UniqueKey: 'Bridge Room : HoloTable'
    Description: 'The Holographic Table is made of a common setup of elements, and
      sequences of events.


      The common elements are the following:'
    Sections:
    - Name: Holographic Table Parallax Elements
      Description: While the mesh of the hologrpahic table is made of a solid, opaque
        material. The items visible inside the table are not actual items. They are
        rendered using a planar parallax shader applied to an inviible plane over
        the surface of the table.
  - Name: 'HoloTable : Idle PinScreen'
    UniqueKey: 'HoloTable : Idle PinScreen'
    Description: 'At the beginning of the Gameplay, The Holographic table displays
      a looping animation of the pin-screen. This animation will be interrupted when
      the player comes close to the table. Triggering the next state of the walkthrough
      : Galaxy Navigation.'
    Sections:
    - Name: Idle Pin Screen VFX
      Description: The Idle Pin Screen VFX is the same as the one used later in the
        sequence. It is using a single Visual Effect and the whole looping animation
        is sequenced using a looping timeline.
    - Name: Going to the next State
      Description: 'Upon Entering the Trigger, the player triggers the state change
        of the State Machine from '
  - Name: 'HoloTable : Solar System'
    UniqueKey: 'HoloTable : Solar System'
    Description: 'Solar System View lets the player choose a planet where to land
      with different degrees of risk. High risk planets cannot be interacted, Selecting
      Low and Medium Risk will advance the walkthrough to the next State : Finding
      Landing Location.'
    Sections:
    - Name: Solar System View
      Description: This view is composed of a sun, Clouds and Asteroid Belts and
        a set of interactive planets.
    - Name: 'Next State : Finding Landing Site'
      Description: Upon selecting a valid target, the State machine advances to the
        next state and performs a transition.
  - Name: 'HoloTable : Galaxy View'
    UniqueKey: 'HoloTable : Galaxy View'
    Description: Galaxy View is the first step of the interactions with the holographic
      table. It presents a galaxy effect with the ship position and three interactive
      destination elements.
    Sections:
    - Name: Galaxy Elements
      Description: Upon activating this state, the pin-screen transitions to galaxy
        view using a timeline.
    - Name: Interactive Items
      Description: Every of the elements is interactive. While the Player Ship's
        interaction does not lead to anything besides displaying its information.
        The other three elements (destination) react to activating them.
    - Name: Going to the Next State
      Description: By selecting one of the three (whatever it is), the navigation
        advances to the next stage. Playing a transition timeline.
  - Name: 'HoloTable : Landing Site'
    UniqueKey: 'HoloTable : Landing Site'
    Description: Landing Site State is a plain animation of the Pin-Screen with a
      target that will define where the ship needs to land.
    Sections:
    - Name: Landing Site Pin-Screen Sequence
      Description: 'This simple sequence is driven by a timeline in order to animate
        the pin-screen and the target VFX. The landing site is displayed using the
        same VFX as galaxy waypoints.


        No interaction from the player is
        required from this point. The next stage is triggered at the end of the timeline.'
    - Name: 'Next State : Alert Mode'
      Description: At the end of the animation, an alarm rings and the player enters
        the final stage of the demo. Ship is being under attack.
  - Name: Core Room Under Attack
    UniqueKey: Core Room Under Attack
    Description: 'The core room holds one big effect that is controlled and animated
      during the attack of the spaceship. While the energy depletes, the core will
      modify its shape until it collapses.


      The effect is made of two distinct
      effects : Core and Rings (used twice), it''s controlled using a timeline.'
    Sections:
    - Name: Core Depletion Sequence.
      Description: 'During the Attack, core energy depletes until the core collapses.

        This
        sequence is orchestrated in a timeline that is controlled by the main timeline
        of the Alert.'
    - Name: Shake "Missile" Events
      Description: "During the attack, big camera shake happen for each missile impact.
        It triggers the sparkles (see \"Sparkle (Shake)\" section in Visual Effects).
        \n\nIn order to preview these events, you can either open the VFX Graph instance
        using the \"Edit\"button next to the field in the inspector, then, in the
        Target GameObject panel of VFX Graph use the \"TakeHit\" Send Button.\nOr
        you can use the Core Hit Timeline that controls both events and parameters."
    - Name: 'Next State : Wrecked Room'
      Description: 'Once core is depleted, a final missile triggers a huge camera
        shake, followed by a blackout.


        Then starts the Wrecked part of
        the demo.'
  - Name: Wrecked Bridge Room
    UniqueKey: Wrecked Bridge Room
    Description: 'After Collapsing, the core shuts down and a final missile hit blacks
      out the player. Then, the player wakes in a destroyed version of the bridge
      room.


      After some delay, the player collapses again then blacks out
      for good, ending the demo.'
    Sections:
    - Name: Effects in the Scene
      Description: 'The scene here is populated with fires on the ground, floating
        sparkles and a blend of smoke and heat deformation.


        (If you cannot
        see the Sparkles, please use the "(Cam)Game" Button on the additional Scene
        View toolbar to toggle Game view tracking.'
  - Name: Fire Pool (Wrecked)
    UniqueKey: Fire Pool (Wrecked)
    Description: 
    Sections:
    - Name: Wrecked Fire Pool
      Description: A Simple Effect of flames going out of a burning fuel Puddle.
        Flames are rendered as flipbook. In order to keep consistent resolution,
        less frames are used but instead blend using Motion Vector flipbook interpolation.
    - Name: Floating Smoke / Ash / Distortion
      Description: 'Ambient VFX Here fills the scene with big smoke and distortion.
        In order to reduce overdraw, Camera Fade and Half Resolution Translucency
        is used.


        Floating ashes also use Tile/Warp in order to loop around
        camera.'
